Brief Hospital Course:
___ yo F with AIDS CD4 41 complicated by HIV nephropathy since 
___ with ESRD on HD ___ presented with R femoral HD line 
infection and was treated with vancomycin.  Her hospital course 
was significant for suspicion of IVC DVT which was ruled out by 
imaging.  She was discharged home after completing an empiric 
course of Vancomycin.

ACTIVE ISSUES

#Line infection: suspected, never bacteremic, s/p empiric 
treatment. 
R ___ U/S was performed to rule out an abscess at the site of her 
AV fistula, no drainable collection.  Patient was treated 
initially with cefepime (which was d/c'd due to low suspicion of 
GNR infection) and 7 days of vancomycin dosed at dialysis 
following line pull (last dose ___.  ___ helped replace a 
tunneled line on the left side without complication.  She never 
developed fever or bacteremia. 

#Suspected IVC thrombus: ruled out by imaging.
Imaging during femoral catheter placement suggested possible 
thrombus in IVC. Hematology was connsulted (anticoagulation in a 
patient with uncertain compliance would be risky).  Heparin was 
started, but after further imaging with CT venogram which showed 
in fact there was no clot, heparin was d/c'd. This was about 24 
hrs after heparin was started.

#Hypotension: Patient initially presented to ED with BP in ___ 
s/p dialysis and finding of infected femoral HD line. Patient 
was given 3L fluid and pressures normalized into the 
___. She was asymptomatic. No further fluid was given 
out of concern for triggering pulmonary edema without HD access. 
Pt tends to become hypotensive during dialysis.

#EKG showing bigeminy: a new finding this admission.
Pt had an EKG done while at HD on ___ due to alarming for 
bradycardia and was noted to have premature atrial beats in a 
bigeminal pattern. Rate was in fact 80. She was asymptomatic and 
hemodynamically stable; repeat EKG on the medical floor no 
longer showed this.

#. h/o AFib: previously undocumented, will increase ASA to 
___.
On reviewing old EKGs due to the incident above, it was noted 
that she has had AFib/RVR in the setting of sepsis in the past 
(specifically on ___ and ___.  Her CHADS2 score is low 
so no clear indication for Warfarin (especially given 
questionable med compliance), but her Aspirin dose was increased 
from 81mg to 325mg daily.

Discharge Instructions:
Dear Ms. ___,

It was our pleasure to care for you at ___.  
You were admitted due to suspicion of an infected right femoral 
hemodialysis line from ___ clinic.  We pulled the line and 
treated you with antibiotics to help control the likely 
infection - now the antibiotic course is complete.  With the 
help of interventional radiology, we were able to place a new 
catheter on the left side.  

During imaging to put your catheter in, it was noted that you 
might have a clot in a big vessel in your body. We started to 
treat that with heparin (an intravenous blood thinner), but this 
therapy was stopped once a CT scan showed that there was no 
clot.

While you were here and at dialysis, your systolic blood 
pressure would often go down into the ___ and ___ and at one 
point we did an EKG to look at your heart and it showed that 
your had changes called bigeminy. You had no symptoms and we did 
not feel it needed to be treated.

Finally, during this admission you had depressed mood.  You 
denied any active suicidal or homicidal thoughts.  You should 
follow up with ___ (Social Worker); you have her 
contact info.  Please call to make an appointment for a visit.

Aspirin")

radiology.text:
CHEST RADIOGRAPH PERFORMED ON ___ 

Comparison to chest radiograph from ___ and CTA chest also from that same
day.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  Hypotension and sepsis, assess for pneumonia.

FINDINGS:  Portable AP upright chest radiograph is obtained.  The lungs are
clear bilaterally without focal consolidation, effusion, or pneumothorax. 
Clips are noted in the right axilla.  The heart size is normal.  There is an
unusual configuration of the mediastinum which is stable from prior exams and
likely reflects the extensive collateral vessels due to known left subclavian
and brachiocephalic venous stenosis.  Bony structures are intact.  No free air
below the right hemidiaphragm.

IMPRESSION:  No acute intrathoracic process.

INDICATION:  Patient with possible femoral dialysis line infection.  Assess
for underlying abscess formation.

COMPARISONS:  None available.

FINDINGS/IMPRESSION:

Targeted ultrasound exam at the site of the patient's previous dialysis
catheter placement in the right proximal thigh demonstrates extensive soft
tissue edema.  No organized or drainable fluid collection is identified. 
Small amount of subcutaneous fluid is present which measures 14 x 5 mm in
maximum ___.  Common femoral vein and artery are patent with
appropriate waveforms.

ATTEMPTED TUNNELED HEMODIALYSIS CATHETER PLACEMENT

OPERATORS:  Drs. ___ (fellow) and ___ (attending
physician).  Dr. ___ was present during key moments of the procedure.

CONTRAST:  None.

MEDICATION:  IV 3 mg Versed over 1 hour and 20 minutes, during which patient's
hemodynamic status was continuously monitored by a trained radiology nurse. 
Moderate sedation could not be administered due to airway IV.

PROCEDURE AND FINDINGS:  Consent was obtained from patient after explaining
the benefits, risks, and alternatives.  Patient was placed supine on the
imaging table in the interventional suite.  Timeout was performed as per ___
protocol.

Under aseptic conditions, sonographic guidance, and after infiltrating the
skin and subcutaneous tissues with adequate amounts of 1% lidocaine, a
micropuncture needle was placed in the patent left common femoral vein at the
level of mid-to-lower femoral head.  Sonographic images were printed prior to
and following needle placement.  A 0.018 wire was advanced through the needle
and into the common iliac vein.  After making incision at the access site, the
needle was exchanged for a 4.5 ___ microsheath.  Inner cannula and wire
were removed to place a 0.035 ___ wire, which was eventually advanced into
the ___.  After appropriate measurements, a site was chosen on the left
anterior thigh.  Skin was infiltrated with 1% lidocaine prior to incision. 
Subcutaneous tissues along the proposed tunnel were infiltrated with a mixture
of lidocaine and epinephrine.  A 15.5 ___ 50 cm (tip-to-cuff) hemodialysis
catheter was tunneled from the skin incision to exit at the venotomy site with
the help of a blunt metallic tunneler.  After removing the microsheath, a
Kumpe catheter was used to exchange the ___ wire for an Amplatz wire, which
was advanced to the ___.  After removing the Kumpe catheter, the tract was
dilated sequentially with 12 and 14 ___ dilators, prior to placing a 16
___ peel-away sheath.  After removing the inner cannula and wire, attempts
were made to advance the catheter via the peel-away sheath; however, we were
unable to completely advance the catheter.  Multiple attempts were made, at
which time the patient wanted to stop the procedure.  She also did not want us
to attempt a temporary dialysis catheter placement at this time.  Sheath was
removed, and firm pressure was applied to the venotomy site for about 10
minutes to achieve complete hemostasis.  Tunneled catheter was also removed. 
Sites were dressed in a sterile fashion.  No immediate post-procedure
complication was seen.

IMPRESSION:  Unsuccessful attempts at placing a tunneled hemodialysis catheter
via the left common femoral vein.  Please see above for details.

Findings were discussed over the phone with Dr. ___, renal fellow, at
4:48 p.m. on ___.

TUNNELED HEMODIALYSIS CATHETER PLACEMENT.

INDICATION:  ___ woman with end-stage renal disease, HIV, on dialysis.

OPERATORS:  Drs. ___ (fellow) and ___ (attending
physician).  Dr. ___ was present during key moments of the procedure.

CONTRAST:  Sterile 15 mL Optiray 320.

ANESTHESIA:  General endotracheal anesthesia provided by the anesthesiologist.

PROCEDURE AND FINDINGS:  Consent was obtained from the patient after
explaining the benefits, risks, and alternatives.  Patient was placed supine
on the imaging table in the interventional suite.  Timeout was performed as
per ___ protocol.

Under aseptic conditions, sonographic guidance, and after infiltrating the
skin and subcutaneous tissues with 1% lidocaine, a micropuncture needle was
placed in the patent left common femoral vein at the level of mid-to-lower
femoral head.  Sonographic images were printed prior to and following needle
placement.  A 0.018 wire was advanced through the needle and into the iliac
vein.  After making an incision at the access site, needle was removed to
place a 4.5 ___ microsheath.  After removing the inner cannula and wire,
0.035 ___ wire was advanced via the microsheath and eventually into the SVC.
After removing the microsheath, the ___ wire was exchanged with a 0.035
stiff Amplatz wire with the help of a 5 ___ Kumpe catheter.  Appropriate
site was chosen on the left anterior thigh.  After making an incision and
infiltrating the subcutaneous tissues along the proposed tunnel, 15.5 ___
50-cm (tip-to-cuff) hemodialysis catheter was tunneled to exit at the venotomy
site with the help of a blunt metallic tunneler.  After removing the Kumpe
catheter, the tract was dilated under fluoroscopy sequentially with 12 and 14
___ dilators, prior to placing a 16 ___ 30-cm peel-away sheath.  After
removing the wire and inner cannula, the tunneled catheter advanced through
the peel-away sheath.  However, it was very difficult to completely advance
the catheter.  A 0.035 ___ wire was placed via the blue lumen of the
catheter and used to help further advance the catheter tip to the level of the
upper IVC.  It was still very difficult to further advance the remaining
portion of the catheter.  Sheath away completely, the catheter was retracted
at the entry site.  After removing the ___ wire, two 0.035 stiff Glidewire
were placed in the lumens of the catheter and advanced into the SVC.  Catheter
was then advanced over these wires to place the tip in the right atrium. 
After removing the wires, we attempted to aspirate and flush the lumens,
however, we were unable to do so.  At this time, catheter tip was repositioned
to different levels, however, we were still unable to aspirate and flush. 
Hence, the catheter was removed over two stiff Glidewire.  A Kumpe catheter
was placed over one of the wires and advanced to the lower IVC.  A small
amount of sterile contrast material was hand injected, which demonstrated
likely partial thrombus in the IVC.  After removing the catheter and one of
the wires, a long 16 ___ peel-away sheath was placed over the second wire
and advanced into the lower IVC.  After removing the inner cannula, a new 15.5
___ 50-cm (tip-to-cuff) hemodialysis catheter was placed over the wires to
partially advance the catheter to the level of left iliac vein.  After peeling
away the sheath, another stiff Glidewire was placed in the other lumen to help
feed the catheter to position tip in the right atrium.  After removing the
wire, we were able to aspirate and flush both the lumens successfully.  Small
amount of sterile contrast material was injected through the blue lumen to
confirm patency and good flush.  Catheters were flushed with saline again.  A
single ___ Vicryl suture was placed in the venotomy site.  Catheter was
secured by 0 silk sutures.  The sites were dressed in a sterile fashion.  The
patient tolerated the procedure well.  No immediate post-procedure
complication was seen.

IMPRESSION:  Uncomplicated ultrasound and fluoroscopy-guided placement of 15.5
___ 50-cm (tip-to-cuff) tunneled hemodialysis catheter via the patent left
common femoral vein and with its tip in the right atrium.  The catheter is
ready for use.  Please note that it was extremely difficult to advance the
catheter past the left common iliac vein and through the IVC.  A small amount
of contrast injected through the IVC demonstrated likely thrombus.  If
clinically indicated, CT venogram or MR venogram may be performed.

Results were discussed over the phone with Dr. ___ at around 3 p.m.
on ___.

CT OF THE ABDOMEN AND PELVIS WITH IV CONTRAST

INDICATION:  ___ woman with incidentally found likely partial thrombus
in the IVC by ___ during placement of a left-sided tunneled line.  Question is
whether this is acute versus chronic thrombus, would affect decision regarding
anticoagulation.

CT OF THE ABDOMEN AND PELVIS WITH AND WITHOUT IV CONTRAST TECHNIQUE: 
Multidetector scanning is performed from the diaphragm through the symphysis
prior to and during dynamic injection of 150 cc of Omnipaque.  No prior
studies are available for comparison.

CT OF THE ABDOMEN WITH AND WITHOUT IV CONTRAST:  There is some atelectasis at
the lung bases.  No lung nodules are noted.  The liver is without focal
lesions.  The gallbladder is unremarkable.  The spleen is normal in size and
contains a 0.9 cm hypodense lesion that is too small to characterize as well
as a 1.9 cm hypodense lesion that measures 43 Hounsfield units.  These are
most consistent with hemangiomas.  The pancreas is unremarkable.  The adrenal
glands are normal.  Multiple renal cysts are noted bilaterally.  A 0.6 cm
calcification is noted in the right kidney.  There is no retroperitoneal
lymphadenopathy.  There is no hydronephrosis.  There is no excretion of
contrast into the renal collecting system.  A catheter is identified in the
IVC and extends into the right atrium.  The IVC is opacified and there is no
evidence for a filling defect that is consistent with a thrombus.

CT OF THE PELVIS WITH IV CONTRAST:  The uterus is unremarkable.  Two follicles
are seen in the right ovary measuring 1.5 and 2.0 cm.  There is no free fluid
in the pelvis.  No pelvic lymphadenopathy is identified.  The pelvic veins are
patent.  In the right groin, there are two stents identified originating from
the common femoral artery and this appeared to be occluded.  Fat stranding is
identified in the left groin surrounding the venous catheter consistent with a
small amount of hemorrhage at the insertion site.

On bone windows, there are no concerning osteolytic or osteosclerotic lesions.

IMPRESSION:
1.  No evidence of thrombosis of the IVC.  The IVC contains a central venous
line and is patent.

2.  Innumerable bilateral renal cysts.

3.  Two splenic lesions most consistent with hemangiomas.
